segments.text: One, two, three.
One, two, three.
One, two, three.
Testing.
Testing.
Three, two, one.
Three, two, one.
Testing.
Three, two, one.
I've already tested these, so they're working.
This is the 21st of September.
We're in 207.
And I have the honor and pleasure of chatting with Admiral William W. Pickavance, Jr.
First of all, to introduce yourself to anyone who would listen to the tape or read a transcription, give a biographical summary of yourself up until the time you came to A&M.
Okay, I was... What did family do and all that?
My mom and dad are from Sherman, Texas, and of course, my dad was in the Air Force during World War II, flew B-24s, got out after

after the war, the day I was born, as a matter of fact, 25th of November, 1945, and went into the hardware business in Fort Worth, where I was born, and at Carswell, and was recalled during the Korean War.
So we were in the military the whole time, had 16 or 17 moves as an Air Force brat, lived overseas in England, and so on and so forth.
And...
Came back, we were stationed in Missouri, where I went to high school, Knob Noster, Missouri.
Started out up in Massachusetts, then down to Knob Noster at Whiteman Air Force Base.

And then in 1961, my sophomore year, middle of my sophomore year, we were transferred to Offutt Air Force Base, where Dad worked at SAC headquarters there and was involved, of course, in the Cuban crisis in 1963.
I graduated in 1964.
I can still remember sitting in my English class when President Kennedy was killed and

immediately going over to my best friend's house whose dad was a two-star general at the time and sat there and watched all that on TV and got the exposure of a very high-ranking officer as he talked about the ramifications of this and all the things that would evolve from it.
I applied to the Naval Academy.
When I was eight years old, I told my mother I'd give a ride on an aircraft carrier someday.
And it's really funny because here growing up in the Air Force, my dad being an Air Force pilot, I'm not real sure where
The Navy came into it.
But I applied to the Naval Academy.
I didn't get in my first year.
I thought I was going to go play football there, and it didn't work out.
So I talked to a bunch of folks.
And Texas A&M had always been a school that we talked about in our family for years.
And my dad was only a major at the time, so he didn't make a lot of money.
And certainly I didn't have any academic qualifications.
I had some football qualifications, but not academic qualifications.
And I knew how to find a date and that kind of stuff, but I didn't focus on academics.
As a matter of fact, to get out of high school, I'll never forget, we had this Spanish teacher, big old, big gal, big gal, had a mustache, I'll never forget it.
Her name was Miss Snavely.
And right before we graduated in 1964 from Bellevue High School there in Nebraska,
I had to, I literally went up and kissed her on the cheek and said, Miss Naval, you can't give me a D. You know, they'll never let me in college.
So she gave me a C minus.
And I got into A&M.
And we came down here.
I intentionally had planned on using it for prep school for the Naval Academy.
Had you visited A&M before?
Never have.
Never been here.
I'd seen all the pictures, and I loved the military part of it.
You know, I really, I knew I wanted to be in the military.
And the only thing you didn't have was Naval ROTC.
And so, and that's kind of how I got into this Galveston process that I'll talk about here in a second, is that we got down here.
I was in Company E2 in Army ROTC.
My initial plan was, because I really struggled.
My uniforms were pressed.
My shoes were shined.
But boy, my eyes were really open.
I just wasn't the, you know, top notch whatever.
And between the, I enjoyed the military rigor more than I enjoyed sitting in a class with 1,000 people, or however many it was.
It was auditorium, like it was just loaded with folks.
And listen to Phil Graham and others try to teach me economics.
You know, I just.
All right, now your dad was stationed at?
at Offutt at the time.
So y'all drove down.
My grandparents lived up in Sherman.
Thank you for bringing that up.
I think the money part of it is something we kind of talked a little bit about it last night.
My dad was a major.
He probably in those days was making a thousand dollars a month.
When I went to school here, and we were Texas residents obviously and had been forever,
Still would like to be, except in Florida, you got to get a Texas driver's license.
First time in my life I've ever had anything other than a Texas driver's license since I moved to Florida.
But at any rate, Dad didn't make a lot of money.
And I can remember when we moved from Missouri to Offutt, we literally lived on rice and beans.
And we were very proud, you know, never lacked for anything.
But you could always tell when Mom and Dad were just a tad strapped.
And God bless them, they always pulled it off somehow.
But you knew it was for a good purpose.
So when I decided to come to school down here, it was quite a, it was hard on my parents.
But, you know, I think in those days the tuition was $50 a semester, and it was $368, you know, for room and boards.
And you couldn't go anywhere in the world and get that kind of an education for that price that I'm aware of.
And so anyway, this is where I came.
Got down here.
I started majoring in history.
Just a second.
Mom and dad brought you?
Oh, yes, sir.
Now let me go to that.
Mom and dad brought me.
What did you bring?
What was the trip like?
Well, it was interesting.
Of course, my dad hadn't been in the Air Force all these years.
We had these military foot lockers.
And...
And Mom had taken all my white towels and my underwear and my undershirts.

And so, I don't know how she did it, but these little bitty name tags, Bill Pickivants, I'll never forget it, little tiny things, you know, that were in all my clothes and all my towels and all this kind of stuff.
And shoeshine gear.
And, of course, they gave you a little list of kind of your, what we call a sea bag in the Navy.
It kind of had a list of things that you need to bring, and then we'll provide the uniforms and the other stuff.
And it was the dirtiest thing I've ever seen.
They brought me.
Of course, they were reared in the Depression, and they were pretty tough folks.
And they dropped me off in front of the registrar's office and then drove off.
And my grandparents came down, too.
We came down from Sherman, and they took my footlocker out of the trunk, put it out in front.
There was kind of a line, and I can remember everybody signing in.
And I'd gotten a haircut.
It wasn't short enough, but I'd gotten a haircut.
I'd always worn a crew cut.
And I sat on that trunk as they drove off down the street.
Of course, I don't even think now you can even drive on that street anymore.
But they drove off, and I thought, my word, this is it.
I'm on my own.
Did your dad give you any, or mom or anybody else, any last-minute advice?
Well...
The usual things.
Son, do the best you can.
You know, you've got to take advantage of this.
Neither one of them had gone to college.
My grandmother, my dad's mother, had gone to Hockaday, I guess it was, in Fort Worth.
And she had graduated from college.
But she was the only one, and I guess my dad's sister had graduated from college.
But dad...
He hadn't even finished high school when he went to Fort Sill to get in the artillery and then got into cadets and was flying B-24s.
My mother
was a tennis player and was a Texas tennis champion and they'd gotten married and they'd eloped just like Nancy and I did 36 years ago.
But neither one of them had gone to college.
So the advice was take advantage of this and do the best you can.
We love you.
Don't call us when you need to.
And I think, of course, they gave me some spending money.
I don't think it was very much.
And then off they went.
And how did you get
from there to an outfit.
How did, as far as you know?
Well, you know, in those days, I'm trying to remember the, it seems to me like you had to walk downstairs where you signed in and you kind of left your trunk there.
And then Terry Archer, who was my roommate, and Terry and I had known each other since we were about eight years old at Westover Air Force Base and other places.
Terry and I each, as I recall, we each carried our trunks together.
And we were official ladies.
What outfit?
Company E2, Shoemaker Hall, over here.
Did it have a nickname?
Reveille was our company.
In fact, it's ironic that now that's the Navy Marine Corps company, which I find interesting.
But we had Reveille, and I can remember whipping out to, Howdy, Ms. Reveille, ma'am.
So we got through all the registration stuff and drug our foot lockers down and
They went back and got our uniforms and we had our ironing boards and our iron and all that kind of stuff.
Our fan, in fact I was getting dressed last night and I said, well I don't remember it being this hot here.
Nancy says, yeah well you were a lot thinner in those days.
But we put our fan in the window and made our racks.
We knew how to do that and
and got ourselves squared away.

As a matter of fact, since both of our dads were in the military, Terry's dad was also in the military, we sort of knew a lot of stuff from listening to our dad's talk about going through cadets and all that.
So we were able to get our bunks made and get our uniforms ironed and cleaned up.
And actually, Butch Trish, who was the company commander, and Arnie Sauge, who was the...
Spell Sauge.
I think it's S-A-L-G-E, from Seguin.
I'll never forget it.
And I forget where Butch Trish was from, but he's really a nice guy.
Tough, but nice.

They kind of used us as examples because we knew how to spit shine shoes and all that and I can remember all the other fish sitting down on the side and we were standing up showing how to put on the brass and all that kind of stuff, get the maiden head off and all that and using the newspaper and Brasso and so that's kind of how it all began.
Describe then the first few days of how
all of the core activities and the good bull and going into the dining hall.
Describe that.
Well, we spent, of course, more time studying

studying all the stuff you had to study to get it to be able to eat, you know, and going through all the, not being informed of the high-score accuracy, particularly if you're ever going to give you a two-course rectitude and short shrub and don't know the answer.
You know, we had to go through all that and learn all those things, and the problem with Terry Archer, who I just love dearly, he's now in Florida, and we're just very, very close.
We're just a great guy.
He turned out to be a very successful contractor, built a lot of buildings in Houston, and has literally built Naples, Florida.
But Terry, God bless him, would never take the time to read the darn menu.
So, you know, we get in formation, and you didn't want to, I don't want to cuss, but F word your fish buddy.
So I'd have the real menu memorized, right?
We'd be standing there at attention, and it'd be eggs all rotten and all this kind of stuff.
Well, Archer would be standing there, and they'd come to him and say, Fish Archer, what's the menu?
Many other days, he'd rattle off just anything.
I mean, anything from hamburgers to filet mignon.
So here I've got the real menu, and I've been reciting it over and over again.
He gives this menu that's completely false, and then they come to me and they say, what's the menu?
And I can remember just getting it all.
Of course, here we all are, you know, doing push-ups.
And everybody was like, pick a piece.
You've got to start learning the menu.
And he never got whacked for it.
It was always me.
I was always the guy that they thought wasn't memorizing the menu.
So those kinds of things were kind of the first shot.

Going down the steps, in those days we wore the khakis, and you couldn't have any wrinkles in the back where your legs normally bend, so you'd kind of go down on the heels of your shoes so you wouldn't bend them.
Making sure your uniform was perfect.
I think the big one was getting out of your hole in the morning because you never knew who was in the passageway.
Generally, Terry would be arcing around the door.
He'd get a little nervous.
I'd just push him out into the passageway.
We came up with this thing that was something like this.
I just kind of
didn't even make sense, and they never seemed to notice.
So it was really, I thought that was kind of interesting.
But I used to be able to remember names.
I tell you, here today,
I think because of that, I don't remember people's names.
It's just amazing.
It's almost a psychological thing because I had to remember so many of them and where they were from and what they were taking and all that kind of stuff.
That first semester, you were officially majoring in history.
Do you remember some courses you took that first semester?
I can remember biology.
I don't remember who the instructor was.
And it was the dirtiest thing.
I remember one case in particular where we were looking at some plants or something under the microscope.
And they really need microscopes over there, you know.
And it's the first time, you know, biology in high school, you didn't have these kind of microscopes.
But this is one of these electron kind of microscopes.
It makes everything look big.
And the prof had handed out some slides that we were supposed to look at and draw or something.
And I was just, God, I just said, holy mackerel.
And I remember he came over and said, what are you talking about here?
And I said, look at that.
Look at that thing eating those other things down there.
And, well, he looked at me and said, well, obviously you haven't studied because that's exactly what you're supposed to be looking at.
You're supposed to be telling me about it.
And so biology, again, I was not, my academic prowess was probably not anywhere near what it should be or should have been in those days, but I learned later on.
And, of course, economics and history and all that other kind of stuff were,
The core was still compulsory.
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
Describe a typical day, Monday through Friday, for you and your outfit.
What time did you all get up?
What happened where?
What did you do when?
It seems to me that...
Our day started six-ish, usually, and we tried to get down to the showers before the upperclassmen got down there so we could run in, get our shower, and get the heck out and not get zapped.
And, of course, get our uniforms ironed and get dressed and get our racks made up and get ourselves in order and get the whole in order, closet and all that kind of stuff.
And then they would fall out for formation, I want to say probably 7ish, 6.30 or 7ish.

And that was when, of course, for the first, it seems like the first three months, we just really got ourselves, every time we turned around, we were getting hollered at and yelled at and all that, the duty stuff.
We kind of took that in stride because we figured that that was what was going to happen.
And you kind of knew who the bad players were.
There were a couple of guys that were,
almost sadistic in some of the stuff they wanted to do.
And I think in that kind of an environment, you will occasionally find that people, there's some folks who really like to do hazing.
And I discovered after, I discovered through the years that they're usually folks that probably didn't have it very hard when they went through it.
Particularly, the little guys particularly like picking on myself and Terry, making us be slaves, if you will.
But then we'd fall out for formation.
And, let's see, you all went to Sabisa.
We went to Sabisa.
Duncan.
Oh, you're a Duncan.
Duncan.
And we'd fall out and, you know, we'd have the, I really liked this part of it.

It'd be early in the morning, be crisp, and, you know, and, you know, everybody would be very formal and add attention and report, you know, and go around the, you know, the whole, the whole Corps there.
Then the Corps commander and his staff would march in and then,
You know, we'd all fall in, and we did that for all three meals my freshman year.
And so you'd go in, go in for breakfast, and if you're sitting on the hot, you know, running the hot table, you were, you know, the corner there, you were a busy fella.
And needless to say, Terry and I didn't get a lot to eat in those days and stayed pretty thin throughout that first year.
Do you remember some foods that you really liked and or really didn't like?
I loved the potatoes au gratin.
I loved the spaghetti because if you ate spaghetti, you could get the meat and everything kind of all in one bite before somebody yelled at you.
I thought the apple pies were just out of this world.
In fact, one day,
a bunch of us freshmen decided, a bunch of fish decided that we were going to get a pie.
So we took our, and it had to wait for a day when it was raining where you had your raincoats and piss pots.
And you could, you know, a helmet would fit right over a pie.
So, and you walked out with your helmet to your side.
So you could literally put a pie up in your helmet and try to walk out with it.
Now, if you got caught,
it was the last time you were going to see daylight.
But we actually, some of us actually managed to get out with it, you know.
And, boy, we devoured it because if they found it, and then what do you do with the pan?
I mean, it was a regular military operation.
I mean, there was a lot of stuff you had to do to make that all work, you know, come off right.
Back to the dorm, then go to class.
Back to the dorm, go to class.
Class was kind of a reprieve.
And, of course, the Memorial Student Center was our place to really
go sleep, because you really didn't get much sleep.

You know, you could be sleeping, and the next thing you know, they'd be banging on your door, and you'd be in there with your helmet, piss pot, and raincoat on, and smoking cigarettes to get the place real smoky with the windows shut, and, you know, it was, you know, you learn to live with stress, you know.
I don't think that at that point in time that we were, and in retrospect, we weren't pushing
academics as hard as we should have been.
And I'm glad to see that Ted Hopgood and others are doing that because that's really the strategic objective.
And that was not as critical, it didn't seem to me like, as some of the other stuff that's going on.
But the other stuff was really kind of fun and challenging.
And give me 68 and one for the Corps and one for the president and one for this and one for that.
So you end up doing 100 push-ups.
And literally, you just kind of rolled into the rack and you were just beat.
But going to class was sort of a reprieve from all that.
But I can remember being really tired and probably not taking as copious notes as I should.
In fact, it was right in this building, in the older part of the building, where we had our Spanish class.
And again, I told you Spanish is not my forte, but you had to take it.
And I thought, well, I'll take Spanish again.
Well, it wasn't Spanish like
It wasn't being taught the way I was kind of used to.
You'd go in, you'd sit in a cube,

and this retired Air Force colonel, I can't remember his name, would give you a tape, or he put the tape in, that's what it was, and then he dialogued through a machine, and that was kind of foreign to me, and unless you really spent some time studying, it was sometimes hard to understand because the tapes weren't good, so I was always trying to listen and go on to the next thing, so I had a tough time with Spanish, so I had to
They had to retake Spanish and finally made an A in it, but subsequently.
And midday, you'd go back to your room.
Midday, you went back, and I can't remember the time.
Did you all fall in?
Oh, yeah, absolutely, absolutely.
And this is when Terry Archer would come up with these culinary menus that would just drive us all crazy.
Then we'd march in, eat, go back, and, of course, now it's 1230 or so, and now you're really tired and sleepy.
And, of course, you had to walk over, and you'd have this big,

auditorium full of people and sit there and try to stay awake and take notes and take tests and then you'd go back after that, get your uniforms pressed for the evening formation and go eat and then come back and study and get interrupted occasionally, frequently.
and then try to get to bed.

I think at 10.30 is when taps hit, or 10, and we'd go to bed, and sometimes if you had a test the next day, you'd study with your flashlight under your sheets, and we'd try to fix our doors where we still got a breeze because it was hot and there was no air conditioning and that kind of stuff.
in the chow hall.
Did you all have cush questions?
Oh, absolutely.
Oh, absolutely.
What were some of your favorites you remember?
Well, you know, of course we were quizzed on every building, brick, tree, tradition, you know, known to mankind, and it's the duty, the duty ones that we all study, and yeah, they kept us busy.
I can remember people crawling around on the tables and lighting the napkins, you know, and as a matter of fact, my

When I commanded an air wing, F-18 air wing, a fellow by the name of Bob Maddox, who graduated in 69 or 70, Marine, Lieutenant Colonel was my executive officer, and another fellow by the name of Dizzy Dean was an Aggie, and he was in the squadron.
He was one of my instructors, F-18 instructor pilots, a Marine.
And Bob Maddox's going away party, he did that same thing.
I hadn't seen it since I was in school, and here it was, 1986, and all of a sudden, you see these flames coming up from these napkins, and...
What had happened is that Maddox used to be one of Dizzy's, I guess, upperclassmen and said, Dean, get over here.
Dean said, get around here and light those napkins.
Everybody was just, what are these guys doing?
There was a lot of that kind of stuff that went on all the time.
I just...
Like I said, I remember tasting some stuff, but I don't ever remember walking out of there where I felt like I was really full.
Most of the time, freshmen all came over to the Memorial Student Center and tried to get something to eat there because you knew you weren't going to get much to eat at the chow hall.
Now, there was no hazing or anything like that in the library?
No.
Or the MSC?
That's right.
Of course, they didn't drop handles, but you could go curl up in a corner there and...
I mean, that was a real sanctuary.
And a couple of times, and I remember what we did.
I'm sure it had to do with Babbo bombs or something.
You know, we kind of, our company sort of split up into what we called the big ones and the little ones.
And we didn't, we wanted to all be the same, but we had some folks that didn't want to cause any trouble.
You know, let's maintain status quo and, you know, we'll get through this and get on and be sophomores, you know, pissheads.
And there was others who said, bullshit, let's take these guys on.
We're smart as they are.
So, you know, excuse my English, but there came that when the Babel bomb started coming and all that.
So it wasn't too long into the semester that, as I recall, we lost our MSC privileges except for our mailbox, because that's where our mailboxes were.
Because of some of the annex we were doing.
And, you know, it was, but I can't remember all of it.
It seems to me like Babel bombs were one, and then, oh, I can remember,
upperclassmen had a tendency, you know, you'd get a care box from home, and my mother, for some reason, liked Divinity Candy, so she thought I did, and I can't stand it.
But Trish loved, my company commander, loved Divinity Candy.
And so these guys would all wander in and eat all this candy.
Well, it didn't really matter because I didn't like it anyway, but I thought that was sort of rude.
So I can remember getting this box, and we kind of advertised it, and then we took shaving cream and put shaving cream on top of all these little... Oh, man, I forget what we lost that time.
Probably our toilet, not the seat privileges.
We had to sit down on the hard part and...
So we caused some problems.
Of course, in those days, getting hit with a broom was great.
Bend over and grab pooch and get whacked with a broom.
That was nothing.
That was wonderful compared to the coat hangers.
The coat hanger one was the one that really got us.
I can remember going into the showers and soaking the khakis off my rear end because of the scab building up on the pockets and all that.
Did they ever use a paddle?
I don't remember a paddle, but boy, they sure used the coat hanger.
You'd take the coat hanger and stretch it out and whack it, and then the broom part.
The broom was great.
I didn't mind that.
Push-ups and stuff weren't bad setups.
Yeah, it doesn't say if you live it, but I thought the coat hanger was a little bit... And in retaliation, you guys never put an animal in anybody's...
Never put an animal in anybody's room or anything like that?
No, we didn't do any of that.

Now, I will tell you, I told you Miss Reveille was our mascot, and, of course, we had to take her out, and she had to go to the bathroom and stuff, and it wasn't all that unusual to find a little bit of that in a babble bomb when it went off.
Now, where was Reveille's room compared to yours?
Goodness, let's see.
I was on, as I recall, we had the second and third, or the...
third and fourth decks, as I recall, or floors, and I want to say she was down on the third.
She was down on the third.
And we had a sophomore, you know, that was her, I'm sure her piss head was still the, you know, takes care of the mascot.
And that was a great honor, wasn't it?
Oh, absolutely.
In fact, it was a great honor to be in Rebel E. I mean, we were all very proud, and...
And we were proud that that we were, we felt tougher than the rest, we felt like we were sort of special that we're kind of handpicked to be in that company.

And we guard her with with our lives, literally, I mean, when we went to football games, remember, I think it was a TCU game, some folks came over and look like they're gonna make a run on on Reveille.
And I mean, the stands empty, and with our company, and when something like that happened, there wasn't any rank structure.
But we were proud of the way we marched.
We were proud of the way our leadership acted and displayed themselves and the presence they had.
And that just kind of rippled down through the rest of us.
Now, in terms of going to class, what were your own personal guidelines about you?
Did you go regularly?
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
The Spanish one I sort of dropped because it just got to where it was starting to interfere with other stuff.
I was just getting further and further behind.
I was getting frustrated, so I went and dropped it.
I think I actually dropped it within the time frame, but it got me some hours behind.
I took fencing and just loved it.
We had an Olympic class fencing instructor here.
I just loved it, and I wish that we'd have carried it on, but it's hard to find somebody else to fence it, so it kind of fell by the wayside.
I was a show don, a black belt in judo, so we had a judo club here that was really good, and we'd go all over Texas to do judo, so that was a lot of fun.
And in class, did you ever go to sleep in class?
Oh, absolutely, absolutely.

You tried not to, obviously, out of respect, but sometimes you're just so tired that, you know, you just, and in the smaller classes it wasn't so bad, but it was in the big auditoriums and, you know, where I tended to doze off.
And I'd look around.
I wasn't the only one.
And you went to class regularly, though.
Absolutely.
Absolutely.
No, I didn't.
I don't remember.
I don't think that was an option.
It seemed to me like the company commander got a list of folks that were not doing that, and you would get, you know, that would just bring more trouble on you.
So, yeah.
And as that first semester is going along, how did you communicate with mom and dad?
By letter, pretty much the whole time.
About how often?
I tried to write at least once a week.
And occasionally on the weekends, we had one phone down on the passageway and we'd call home.
But I remember when my mid-semester grades came out, I wasn't doing real hot.
And that was about the time, I want to think it was way or something was happening, and Dan Rather was showing pretty severely wounded folks on tanks.
And I'll never forget my dad saying, son, unless you knuckle down here, that's what's going to happen to you.
Now get your act together.
And I did.
But that's also about the time that, because you recall, I wanted to be in the Navy.
That's what I wanted to do, was fly in the Navy and command an aircraft carrier.
And that was about the time I found out about this place called the Texas Maritime Academy that was being built.
And I loved going to see.
The whole time I was in high school, for the summer, I'd write American President lines and all these different things in National Geographic to see if I could just come and just, I'd work for free.
But I just wanted to get on a steamer and just go places and see things.
So that's when I got into the Texas Maritime Academy.
All right.
You don't go home until Thanksgiving?
No, no.
As a matter of fact, I spent Thanksgiving with my grandparents.
And that was interesting.
Myself and another guy that lived in Sherman, Texas, I wish I could remember his name, left here and drove to Sherman.
And, of course, we had the clubs here for the different towns, and that's where I met him, which was a great idea because some folks had cars, others didn't.
I wasn't.
I wasn't rich enough to do that.
In fact, I had to sell a 52 MGTD just to get some other money to help Dad pay for the school.
We spent Thanksgiving with my grandparents.
I can't remember if my parents stroked down or not, but I can remember laying on my grandmother's couch on Sunday when we had to drive back.
Boy, I tell you, it took all the guts I could muster.
